# Longevity Platform — Project Rules

This is a Next.js 14 longevity/health SaaS web app. Follow these rules in all code:

1. Use Next.js 14+ with App Router (NOT Pages Router)
2. TypeScript strict mode — no `any` types unless absolutely necessary
3. Server Components by default; Client Components only when needed (state, hooks, interactivity)
4. Use Server Actions for mutations when possible, not API routes
5. Use shadcn/ui components — never recreate basic UI from scratch
6. Tailwind CSS for styling; no inline styles, no CSS modules
7. Use Supabase Auth helpers from @supabase/ssr (not the older auth-helpers)
8. Mobile-first responsive design — every page must work on phone
9. Group related components in feature folders, not by type
10. Keep files under 200 lines — split if larger
11. Always handle loading states and error states explicitly
12. Don't install new dependencies without explaining why first
13. Write clear code over clever code — a junior dev should be able to maintain it
14. Add JSDoc comments on complex functions
15. Use descriptive variable names; no abbreviations like `u`, `p`, `data`
16. Always validate user input on the server, not just client
17. Never expose API keys to the client
18. Use environment variables for all secrets, never hardcode

# Brand & Design

- Brand feel: modern, premium, trustworthy, science-backed health platform
- Reference apps: Levels Health, Bryan Johnson's Blueprint, Hone Health, Cal AI
- Primary color: deep teal/green (#0d9488 family)
- Typography: Inter for body
- Generous whitespace, rounded corners (8-12px), subtle shadows
- Avoid generic "AI startup" purple/gradient look

# Working Style

- Walk me through what you're doing as you do it
- After major changes, suggest I commit to git
- If you're unsure about a design decision, ask before implementing
- Test that the dev server still runs after major changes